<body><div class=WordSection1>
<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>🧱 WD001 — Build, Style &amp; Box It Up</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Make a real web page, style it from a <code>main.css</code> file, then group it with <code>&lt;div&gt;</code>s · <strong>Course:</strong> Web Design: CSS · <strong>Time:</strong> about 90 minutes</p>
<p>In this worksheet you build a small web page from nothing, then style it with <strong>CSS</strong> kept in its own file called <strong><code>main.css</code></strong>. Real websites keep their styles in a separate file so the HTML stays clean and one stylesheet can paint the whole site. You will do it that way from day one.</p>
<p>Your page will have a heading, a few paragraphs, a <strong>weekly timetable</strong>, some <strong>buttons</strong>, and a couple of <strong>inputs</strong>. Then you will learn the most useful container in web design: the <strong><code>&lt;div&gt;</code></strong> — an invisible box you put things inside so you can move and style them <strong>as a group</strong>.</p>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each bit of code. Before you imagine the browser drawing it, write what you think shows up.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;head&gt;
  &lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; href=&quot;main.css&quot;&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>This line connects an HTML page to a separate file called <code>main.css</code>. If <code>main.css</code> is empty, does the page change? When does the styling actually appear?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;button&gt;Click me&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;input placeholder=&quot;your name&quot;&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What do you think these two look like on the page? Which one can you type into?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p>In <code>main.css</code>:</p>
<pre><code class="language-css">button {
  background-color: tomato;
  color: white;
}
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The HTML did not change — only <code>main.css</code> did. What happens to every button on the page? Why does the HTML not need editing?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;div&gt;
  &lt;h1&gt;Coco&lt;/h1&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;My cat.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>A <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> is invisible. Do you think you will <em>see</em> a box on screen? Write your guess.</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each bit of code below was meant to do something but is broken. Read what it is <strong>supposed</strong> to do, rewrite it so it works, then explain why the original was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — This is supposed to connect the page to its stylesheet, but no styles ever show up.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; href=&quot;mian.css&quot;&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the file is named <code>main.css</code>. Read the filename letter by letter.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — This CSS in <code>main.css</code> is supposed to make all paragraphs gray.</p>
<pre><code class="language-css">p {
  color = gray;
}
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> in CSS you do not use <code>=</code>. Look at how <code>color: white;</code> was written above.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — This <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> is supposed to wrap a heading and a paragraph together, but the box never closes.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;div&gt;
  &lt;h1&gt;About Me&lt;/h1&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;I like coding.&lt;/p&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> every <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> needs a matching <code>&lt;/div&gt;</code>.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Build the Page 🏗️</h2>
<p>Open Replit and start a new HTML project. You will make <strong>two files</strong>: <code>index.html</code> for the content and <code>main.css</code> for the styles. Link them in the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code>.</p>
<p>Your page is a little "My Week" page. It needs all of these:</p>
<ul>
<li>a <strong>heading</strong> with a title,</li>
<li>a few <strong>paragraphs</strong> about your week,</li>
<li>a <strong>weekly timetable</strong> (a table with the days and what you do),</li>
<li>two <strong>buttons</strong>,</li>
<li>two <strong>inputs</strong> people can type into.</li>
</ul>
<p>Start from this and change the words to be about you:</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
  &lt;title&gt;My Week&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; href=&quot;main.css&quot;&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
  &lt;h1&gt;My Week&lt;/h1&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Hi, I'm ___. Here is what my week looks like.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;My favorite day is ___ because ___.&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;table&gt;
    &lt;tr&gt;
      &lt;th&gt;Day&lt;/th&gt;
      &lt;th&gt;What I do&lt;/th&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;tr&gt;
      &lt;td&gt;Monday&lt;/td&gt;
      &lt;td&gt;___&lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;tr&gt;
      &lt;td&gt;Tuesday&lt;/td&gt;
      &lt;td&gt;___&lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;tr&gt;
      &lt;td&gt;Wednesday&lt;/td&gt;
      &lt;td&gt;___&lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
  &lt;/table&gt;

  &lt;p&gt;Sign up to hear about my week:&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;input placeholder=&quot;your name&quot;&gt;
  &lt;input placeholder=&quot;your email&quot;&gt;
  &lt;button&gt;Sign up&lt;/button&gt;
  &lt;button&gt;Clear&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>A <code>&lt;table&gt;</code> is made of rows (<code>&lt;tr&gt;</code>). Header cells use <code>&lt;th&gt;</code>, normal cells use <code>&lt;td&gt;</code>. Add more days if you like.</p>
<p>Run it. Right now it looks plain — that is fine. We style it next.</p>
<p><strong>Write one sentence: what does your timetable show, and what do your two buttons say?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Style It With <code>main.css</code> 🎨</h2>
<p>Now open <code>main.css</code> (the empty file) and make the page look good. Everything you write here paints the page through the <code>&lt;link&gt;</code> you already added — you do <strong>not</strong> touch <code>index.html</code> again.</p>
<p>Each rule picks an element (<code>body</code>, <code>h1</code>, <code>table</code>, <code>button</code>, <code>input</code>) and changes how it looks:</p>
<pre><code class="language-css">body {
  background-color: beige;
  font-family: Arial;
}

h1 {
  color: darkblue;
}

p {
  color: gray;
}

table {
  border: 1px solid darkblue;
}

th, td {
  padding: 8px;
}

button {
  background-color: tomato;
  color: white;
  padding: 10px;
  border-radius: 8px;
}

input {
  padding: 8px;
}
</code></pre>
<p>Type these into <code>main.css</code>, run the page, then make it yours:</p>
<ul>
<li>change the <code>background-color</code> and the <code>h1</code> color,</li>
<li>give the <code>button</code> a color you like,</li>
<li>add <code>padding</code> to a cell or input to space it out.</li>
</ul>
<p><code>padding</code> adds space <strong>inside</strong> an element so text does not touch the edge.</p>
<p><strong>Write the three colors you chose and where each one goes:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Run the page. What changed the moment you saved <code>main.css</code>? Did any rule not work the way you expected?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>5 · Group It With a <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> 📦</h2>
<p>Right now everything floats down the page on its own. A <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> lets you wrap parts into one box you can style as a group.</p>
<p>In <code>index.html</code>, wrap your sign-up parts in a <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> with a class name:</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;div class=&quot;signup&quot;&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Sign up to hear about my week:&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;input placeholder=&quot;your name&quot;&gt;
  &lt;input placeholder=&quot;your email&quot;&gt;
  &lt;button&gt;Sign up&lt;/button&gt;
  &lt;button&gt;Clear&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>Then style that box in <code>main.css</code>. A <code>.</code> before the name means "the element with this class":</p>
<pre><code class="language-css">.signup {
  background-color: white;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 2px solid darkblue;
  border-radius: 12px;
}
</code></pre>
<p>Run it. Your sign-up section is now one tidy card, and everything inside moved together.</p>
<p><strong>In your own words: what does a <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> do, and why is it useful to wrap things in one?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>6 · Record Your Walkthrough 🎥</h2>
<p>Take a photo or short video of your finished page and show both files. Talk through it like you are teaching someone new. Try to use these words: <strong>HTML</strong>, <strong>main.css</strong>, <strong>link</strong>, <strong>table</strong>, <strong>div</strong>.</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Show your finished page in the browser.</li>
<li>Show <code>main.css</code> and read one rule, then point to what it changes on the page.</li>
<li>Point to your timetable and your <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> and say what is inside each.</li>
<li>Explain why the styles live in a separate file.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Plan what you will say below before you record — you can read from it while filming.</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
